hook.real_world_problem:
You want to write a utility method `getFirst(List<T>)` that returns the first element of any list, or a default value if empty. Without generic methods, you'd have to write separate versions for every type:

```java
// Without generic methods — redundant:
static String  getFirstString(List<String>  list) { return list.isEmpty() ? null : list.get(0); }
static Integer getFirstInt(List<Integer>    list) { return list.isEmpty() ? null : list.get(0); }
static Product getFirstProduct(List<Product> list) { return list.isEmpty() ? null : list.get(0); }
// ... one per type, forever
```

Or use Object and lose type safety:
```java
static Object getFirst(List<?> list) { return list.isEmpty() ? null : list.get(0); }
// But caller needs to cast: String s = (String) getFirst(names); // ugh
```

**With a generic method:**
```java
static <T> T getFirst(List<T> list, T defaultValue) {
    return list.isEmpty() ? defaultValue : list.get(0);
}

// Caller — no casts, type inferred automatically:
String  s = getFirst(names, "unknown");      // T inferred as String
Integer n = getFirst(numbers, 0);            // T inferred as Integer
Product p = getFirst(products, defaultProduct); // T inferred as Product
```

One method. Any type. Type-safe. This is exactly how `Collections.min()`, `Collections.sort()`, and `Arrays.asList()` work. Today you learn to write them.

concept_explanation.syntax:
**Generic method syntax:**

```java
// The <T> comes BEFORE the return type:
public static <T> T getFirst(List<T> list, T defaultValue) {
    return list.isEmpty() ? defaultValue : list.get(0);
}

//        ↑       ↑
//  declares T   uses T as return type and parameter type
```

**Anatomy of a generic method:**
```java
[access] [static] <TypeParams> ReturnType methodName(parameters) {
    ...
}

// Examples:
public static  <T>     T      getFirst(List<T> list, T def)
public static  <T>     List<T> repeat(T item, int n)
public         <T, R>  R      transform(T input, Function<T, R> fn)
```

**Where `<T>` goes**: BEFORE the return type. This is the declaration — it tells Java 'this method introduces a new type parameter T.'

**Compare with generic class:**
```java
// Class: <T> on class declaration — all methods share it
class Box<T> { T get() { ... } }  // T declared on class, used in method

// Method: <T> on the method — independent type parameter
static <T> T getFirst(List<T> list) { ... }  // T declared here, local to method
```

concept_explanation.type_inference:
**Type inference** — the compiler figures out T from the arguments:

```java
public static <T> T getFirst(List<T> list, T defaultValue) { ... }

List<String>  names    = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj");
List<Integer> numbers  = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3);

// Type inferred from arguments:
String  s = getFirst(names, "unknown");  // T = String (from List<String>)
Integer n = getFirst(numbers, -1);       // T = Integer (from List<Integer>)

// The compiler sees: names is List<String> → T must be String
// Then checks: second arg 'unknown' IS a String → OK
// Then knows return type is T = String → OK to assign to String
```

**Explicit type witness** (rarely needed):
```java
// When inference can't figure it out, specify explicitly:
List<String> empty = Collections.<String>emptyList();  // explicit <String>
String s = Collections.<String>emptyList().get(0);     // explicit too

// Most of the time, inference works:
List<String> empty = Collections.emptyList();  // infers from context
```

You almost never need to specify the type explicitly — the compiler infers it in 99% of cases.

concept_explanation.static_utility_methods:
**Generic static utility methods** — the bread and butter:

```java
public class CollectionUtils {

    // Get first element or default
    public static <T> T firstOrDefault(List<T> list, T defaultValue) {
        return list.isEmpty() ? defaultValue : list.get(0);
    }

    // Get last element or default
    public static <T> T lastOrDefault(List<T> list, T defaultValue) {
        return list.isEmpty() ? defaultValue : list.get(list.size() - 1);
    }

    // Repeat a value n times into a list
    public static <T> List<T> repeat(T value, int times) {
        List<T> result = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < times; i++) result.add(value);
        return result;
    }

    // Zip two lists into pairs
    public static <A, B> List<Pair<A, B>> zip(List<A> as, List<B> bs) {
        int size = Math.min(as.size(), bs.size());
        List<Pair<A, B>> result = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) result.add(new Pair<>(as.get(i), bs.get(i)));
        return result;
    }

    // Safe cast — returns null instead of ClassCastException
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public static <T> T safeCast(Object obj, Class<T> clazz) {
        return clazz.isInstance(obj) ? (T) obj : null;
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.generic_instance_methods:
**Generic instance methods** — when a method on a non-generic class needs a type parameter:

```java
// Non-generic class, but method needs type flexibility:
class DataProcessor {
    private List<Object> buffer = new ArrayList<>();

    // Generic instance method — has its own <T>
    public <T> T process(T input, Function<T, T> transform) {
        T result = transform.apply(input);
        buffer.add(result);
        return result;
    }

    // Another generic instance method
    public <T> List<T> getBufferedAs(Class<T> clazz) {
        return buffer.stream()
            .filter(clazz::isInstance)
            .map(clazz::cast)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}
```

Generic instance methods let non-generic classes have type-safe methods.

concept_explanation.method_vs_class_parameter:
**When to put `<T>` on the method vs the class:**

**Put `<T>` on the CLASS** when:
- The type is central to the object's identity
- Multiple methods share the same T
- The T describes WHAT the object holds

```java
class Box<T> {      // T on class — Box IS a Box of T
    T get() { ... } // methods use class's T
    void set(T v) { ... }
}
```

**Put `<T>` on the METHOD** when:
- The type is specific to one operation
- The class works on multiple unrelated types
- It's a static utility method (no 'this' context)

```java
class CollectionUtils {  // no class type parameter
    static <T> T first(List<T> list) { ... }   // T per method
    static <A, B> List<Pair<A,B>> zip(List<A> a, List<B> b) { ... }
}
```

**Hybrid** — generic class + generic method with its own parameter:
```java
class Container<T> {
    private T value;

    // Uses class T:
    public T get() { return value; }

    // Has OWN R — independent of class T:
    public <R> Container<R> map(Function<T, R> fn) {
        return new Container<>(fn.apply(value));
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.java_library_generic_methods:
**Java library generic methods you've been using:**

```java
// Arrays.asList — generic static method
public static <T> List<T> asList(T... a)
// Usage: Arrays.asList("a", "b", "c") — T inferred as String

// Collections.sort — generic static method  
public static <T extends Comparable<? super T>> void sort(List<T> list)
// Works for any Comparable type

// Collections.min / max — generic static method
public static <T extends Object & Comparable<? super T>> T min(Collection<? extends T> coll)
// Returns the minimum element

// Optional.of — generic static method
public static <T> Optional<T> of(T value)
// T inferred from value

// Objects.requireNonNull — generic static method
public static <T> T requireNonNull(T obj, String message)
// Returns T — that's why you can chain: this.name = Objects.requireNonNull(name, ...)
```

Every time you've called these methods, you've been calling generic methods. The T was being inferred from your arguments.

